      "summary": "Book of Enoch — Grokipedia Search ⌘K Suggest Edit Sign in Sign in Overview and Canonicity General Description Canonical Status in Judaism Canonical Status in Christianity Status in Other Religions Manuscript Tradition Ge&#39;ez (Ethiopic) Version Aramaic Fragments from Qumran Greek Translations Other Language Fragments Modern Translations Historical Context and Composition Origins and Authorship Dating and Development Role in Second Temple Judaism Preservation and Rediscovery Content Summary The Book of the Watchers (Chapters 1-36) The Book of Parables (Chapters 37-71) The Astronomical Book (Chapters 72-82) The Book of Dream Visions (Chapters 83-90) The Epistle of Enoch (Chapters 91-108) Notable or Striking Passages Giants and Their Atrocities (Book of the Watchers, Chapter 7) Noah&#39;s Miraculous Birth (Epistle of Enoch / Book of Noah Fragment, Chapters 106–107) Hybrid Offspring in the Animal Apocalypse (Dream Visions, Chapter 86) Primordial Monsters Leviathan and Behemoth (Parables / Noachic Material, Chapter 60) Themes and Motifs Angelology: Watchers and Fallen Angels Apocalyptic Visions and Eschatology Astronomical and Calendrical Knowledge Ethical Teachings and Woes Biblical Presuppositions and Allusions Influence and Legacy Impact on the New Testament Reception in Early Church Fathers Role in Jewish Mysticism and Kabbalah Modern Interpretations and Scholarship Glossary of Key Terms Misconceptions: Relation to Gnosticism References Fact-checked by Grok 2 months ago Book of Enoch Ara Eve Leo Sal 1x The Book of Enoch (Hebrew: סֵפֶר חֲנוֹךְ, romanized: Sēfer Ḥănōḵ), also known as 1 Enoch , the Ethiopic Book of Enoch , or Kitabu cha Henoko in Swahili (though no publicly available Swahili translation or PDF exists), is an ancient Jewish apocalyptic text traditionally ascribed to Enoch , the biblical patriarch and great-grandfather of Noah described in Genesis 5:18–24 as having &quot;walked with God &quot; before being taken to heaven . Composed by